         <div class="row">
               <div class="col-2">
               </div>
  
               <div class="col-8">
                    <h4><br><center></center></h4>
                    <br>
                    <p> 
                        Countries such as the United States, China, and Japan residing in the top left quarter of the plot with high GDP and low CPI are economically prosperous while countries in the bottom left quarter with low GDP and low CPI are economically disadvantaged. The countries on the top right have higher CPI generally due to growth inflation while those in the bottom right exhibit symptoms of stagflation. No conclusions can be drawn on the relationship between total population and economic prosperity.               
                  </p>
               </div>
  
               <div class="col-2">
               </div>
           </div>
           <div class="jumbotron">
               <h3><center>Analyzing the 2016 Labor Market with respect to Gender</center></h3>
                  <br>
                  <br>The percentage of male and female unemployment in the labor market is collected and compiled by national authorities and by international development agencies, including the World Bank. The collaboration of thematic and statistical experts across these organizations helps ensure that the data is robust, reliable, and timely.
                  <br><br><p class="font-italic">Source: The World Bank, World Development Indicators: <a style="color: lightseagreen" href="http://wdi.worldbank.org/table/2.5" target = "_blank"> Unemployment </a>
             </p>
         </div>

         <div class="row">
             <div class="col-12"><center>
                  <div id="hbar"></div>
                  </center>
             </div>
         </div>

         <div class="row">
               <div class="col-2">
               </div>
  
               <div class="col-8"><center>
                  <br>
                    <h4>Insights</h4></center>
                    <br>
                    <p>The data shows unemployed females generally represent a larger percentage of the labor market.  This is seen across multiple global regions, notably in the Middle East and Africa as well as Latin America and the Caribbean.  The Middle East also has the highest percentage of male unemployment.  Asia and North America show the lowest unemployment rates for both male and females.  Country income does not impact unemployment as drastically as region.  Across all country income classes, unemployment ranges between 4% - 6.5%.  Eswatini has the highest rate of male unemployment (25.9%) while the West Bank and Gaza has the highest rate of female unemployment (44.7%).</p>
               </div>
  
               <div class="col-2">
               </div>
           </div>

